did.unittitle: Rice University Harry Clay Hanszen College Records
did.abstract: Hanszen College is one of the four original colleges, which were established to house students. The college is named for Harry Clay Hanszen, a wealthy Texas oilman, who served as chairman of Rice's Board of Governors from 1946 to 1950. Formats include Cabinet meeting minutes, correspondence, news clippings, publications, handbooks, videos, brochures and theatrical events programs.

bioghist.head: Historical Sketch
bioghist.p: Hanszen College is one of the four original colleges, which were established to house students. The college is named for Harry Clay Hanszen, a wealthy Texas oilman, who served as chairman of Rice's Board of Governors from 1946 to 1950.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The collection documents the regular business of Rice University's Harry Clay Hanszen College. Formats include Cabinet meeting minutes, correspondence, news clippings, publications, handbooks, videos, brochures and theatrical events programs.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Stored off-site at the Library Service Center. Please request this material via woodson@rice.edu or call 713-348-2586.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: This material is open for research.

accruals.head: Accruals
accruals.p: Future additions are expected for this material.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Harry Clay Hanszen College Records, 1963-2018, Woodson Research Center, Fondren Library, Rice University

relatedmaterial.head: Related Papers
relatedmaterial.p: See the William H. Masterson Papers, which include a scrapbook made by Hanszen College and Orvetta Masterson's notes for Masters events. See Rice University Archives for records of other Rice University residential colleges. Contact Woodson Research Center staff for assistance.

userestrict.head: Use Restrictions
userestrict.p: Permission to publish from the Harry Clay Hanszen Records must be obtained from the Woodson Research Center, Fondren Library, Rice University.
